curity and intelligence agencies; over twenty senior personnel agreed to be interviewed.Theoretically the author demonstrates the utility to the analysis of national security policy of three conceptual models of historical institutionalism, governmental politics and threat evaluation. The text is of interest to scholars of Security Studies, International Relations and Politics, as well as state and NGO personnel, journalists and general readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  a9/11.  aBertie Ahern.  aIrish Prime Minister.  aIrish immigration policy.  aIrish national security.  aTaoiseach.  aradicalisation.  asecuritisation.  asecurity services.  athreat evaluation.1 aMulqueen, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779330040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847793300423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847793300/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles